summarize the following into a single paragraph using positive and lay language.




Background, Motivation, and Vision




Our environments are geęing smarter. We have seen an increasing number of smarts around us such as wearables, voice assistants, service robots, autonomous vehicles, and a broader array of connective objects in IoT. My research creates enabling sensing and actuation technologies on these smart devices to make ambient intelligence more powerful in facilitating the future of work, healthcare, and education, making our physician environments sustainable and accessible to all.




Pillar 1: Create sustainable ambient intelligence




My research creates sustainable computing technologies that lower the carbon footprint of ambient intelligence while improving its practicality in real-world applications. My lab has been developing novel self-sustaining sensing and actuation systems that monitor events and facilitate user activities running on energy harvested from user interactions (e.g., kinetic movement of people). Overall, this research pillar directly addresses sustainability in the design of computing and enables ambient intelligence to be applied with a minimal negative impact on the environment.




Pillar 2: Use ambient intelligence to improve real-world access for people with disabilities




Ambient intelligence also opens new opportunities for making the physical world equally accessible to all.




Speciﬁcally, my research develops systems that can digitize the physical world for accessibility applications, including XR and AI techniques that allow people with disabilities to beęer navigate through a world full of barriers and inaccessible information. My research also creates intelligent sensing and actuation systems that can be easily utilized by people with motor impairments (e.g., users of wheelchairs) for independent living and improved life qualities.




Pillar 3: Create tools to facilitate the development of ambient intelligence




Finally, my research aims to empower everyone to create ambient intelligence. We believe that people should be able to create ambient intelligence as easily as switching a lightbulb. Besides sponsoring the community with toolkits of existing research, my research also seeks general-purpose frameworks and tools that can be easily used by people with various levels of experience for developing ambient intelligent systems. Ongoing research in this pillar includes 1) creating open-source construction kits, and 2) developing programming tools for developers of energy-harvesting self-sustaining IoT systems.

give a one sentence summary based on the following:

Automating operations of objects has made life easier and more convenient for billions of people, especially those with limited motor capabilities. On the other hand, even able-bodied users might not always be able to perform manual operations (e.g., both hands are occupied), and manual operations might be undesirable for hygiene purposes (e.g., contactless devices). As a result, automation systems like motion-triggered doors, remote-control window shades, contactless toilet lids have become increasingly popular in private and public environments. Yet, these systems are hampered by complex building wiring or short battery lifetimes, negating their positive benefits for accessibility, energy saving, healthcare, and other domains. In this paper we explore how these types of objects can be powered in perpetuity by the energy generated from a unique energy source – user interactions, specifically, the manual manipulations of objects by users who can afford them when they can afford them. Our assumption is that users’ capabilities for object operations are heterogeneous, there are desires for both manual and automatic operations in most environments, and that automatic operations are often not needed as frequently for example, an automatic door in a public space is often manually opened many times before a need for automatic operation shows up. The energy harvested by those manual operations would be sufficient to power that one automatic operation. We instantiate this idea by upcycling common everyday objects with devices which have various mechanical designs powered by a general-purpose backbone embedded system. We call these devices, MiniKers. We built a custom driver circuit that can enable motor mechanisms to toggle between generating powers (i.e., manual operation) and actuating objects (i.e., automatic operation). We designed a wide variety of mechanical mechanisms to retrofit existing objects and evaluated our system with a 48-hour deployment study, which proves the efficacy of MiniKers as well as shedding light into this people-as-power approach as a feasible solution to address energy needed for smart environment automation.

Research

As our world becomes increasingly smart with devices like wearables, voice assistants, and autonomous vehicles, Yang’s research focuses on developing technologies that make these devices more sustainable, accessible, and user-friendly. 

First, his research designs eco-friendly sensing systems that power themselves through everyday movements, reducing their environmental impact. For example, MiniKers is a system that harnesses energy from users' manual interactions with objects—such as doors and window shades—to enable sustainable, automatic operations in smart environments, offering an energy-efficient solution to enhance accessibility and convenience while reducing reliance on complex wiring and frequent battery replacements. 

Second, Yang’s work uses ambient intelligence to create tools that make physical spaces more accessible for people with disabilities, helping them navigate and interact with the world independently. For example, WheelPose is a configurable data synthesis pipeline that generates realistic, diverse synthetic data of wheelchair users using motion capture and Unity simulations, validated through human and AI evaluations to improve pose estimation accuracy for wheelchair users.

Last but not least, some of Yang’s effort is on creating easy-to-use toolkits and frameworks to empower anyone, regardless of experience, to build and use ambient intelligence technology, making this advanced field as approachable as turning on a light switch.

Publications

Yang has published 20 conference/journal papers since he joined UCLA, over half of which were led by his group. Yang’s group has been publishing in top venues in Human-Computer Interaction, such as CHI, UIST, and IMWUT. Publishing in these top HCI venues has become significantly more competitive over the recent years. At CHI, for instance, the acceptance rate has hovered around 24-26% in recent years, with over 3,500 submissions in 2023 alone, marking a sharp rise in volume and selectivity. Notably, Yang’s group has also been winning four paper or demo awards, indicating that some of their work ranks the very top in the HCI community. Yang’s other publications also demonstrate his collaboration with other research groups, which further adds to the productivity of his publishing records.

Funding

Yang has had two collaborative NSF SMALL grants soon after he joined UCLA, which demonstrates his ability to quickly learn, carry out, and, most importantly, succeed in fundraising responsibilities. Such early success and experience should well position him to pursue further funding opportunities as he approaches tenure. based on the reviews below, write 1) a summary of what this proposal is about and 2) a recommendation with the sentiment that the proposal has lots of exciting and positive elements yet also present obvious flaws and clear areas for improvement.




the reviews:




INTELLECTUAL MERIT

Strengths:

- The vision of enabling scientific exploration in hostile and austere environments is an important one and well justified as the backdrop of a CAREER project

- The focus on measurements allows the project to zero in and go deep into a specific yet valuable problem in the context of the above-mentioned vision

- The experimental protocols in RT1 is very detailed and well thought out

Weaknesses:

- Assuming the goal is to investigate measurement methods of MAT performance in scientific exploration in hostile and austere environments—What is the purpose of RT1? Fig 1 says RT1 is about “What to measure” but it seems we already know what to measure (CW, SA, stress, etc.) but what is unknown is how these measurements differ when it comes to MATs in hostile and austere environments.

- In RT1 the experiment is based on a simulative environment, yet operating in an actual hostile and austere environments must feel very different (definitely much more challenging, cognitively-demanding, and stressful) than a simulated one. How would such a discrepancy affect the validity of findings?

- In RT2, will the PI conduct the contextual inquiry in an actual hurricane hunting team’s task? Unlike a typical safe and stable task environment, it seems quite operationally challenging to follow and observe those team members closely in such a hostile environment and situation. The lack of contextual inquiry protocol details makes it less clear how RT2 is feasible and how the PI plans to overcome some of these operational challenges.

- In RT2, what/where are the MAT aspects, i.e., how does the agents team up with humans?

- RT2 seems more like an engineering step, preparing for the apparatus for RT3. Is there intellectual merit in the measurement suite and what are the methods (besides putting together multiple COTS sensors) that innovate such a system?

- The overall framing of the proposal might benefit from scoping down to a specific domain (e.g., disaster research and relief) rather than the general “scientific exploration” that seems too large to tackle in a single project.




BROADER IMPACTS

Strengths:

- The course development is tightly connected to the overall research theme

- There is a detailed assessment plan and collaboration with educational patterns at the PI’s home institute

- The two-way integration of research and education is well formulated, strengthening both the research and educational aspects of this proposal

- The bilingual seminar series seems an innovative and unique activity that situates itself in a research-relevant context (location) yet benefit the local community

Weaknesses:

- None observed.

summarize the following into two lists of bullets: strengths and weaknesses:




1. What is the potential for the proposed activity to advance knowledge and understanding within its own field or across different fields?




Strength:

- Alignment problem—a fundamental challenge of ensuring that AI is doing what a human actually wants it to do.




Areas for Improvements:

- The over scope of human-centered AI seems to broad. It’d be great to define a narrower subset of problems to encompass the proposed work.




2. To what extent do the proposed activities suggest and explore creative, original, or potentially transformative concepts?




Strength:

- Aim 1.1: The problem of suboptimal demonstration where AI’s learning is bounded by demonstrators’ performance is a well-founded and well-motivated issue

- Aim 1.2: The problem of humans “not knowing what we want” is well formulated as a challenge for conventional RL methods




Areas for Improvements:

- The proposal could have answered this question better in the intro section: What’s the unique approach and how does it distinguish itself from prior work? Why are the  proposed research thrusts “foundational” to alignment? For example, is there a gap in literature that motivates the pursuit of these two thrusts? The literature review is embedded in each aim but lacks a more holistic view.

- Aim 1.1: Seems incremental from prior work D-REX

- Aim 1.1: A little too abstract-what’d be an example to show the benefits of learning from multimodal demonstration?

- Aim 1.2: Can some explicit models of how humans learn their preferences (analogous to the power law of learning) help with this aim? Having such a theoretical backbone should strengthen the proposed method

- Aim 2.1: The assumption here seems to be at odds with Aim 1’s. Aim 1 argues that humans performance can be suboptimal and their behavior can be evolving with uncertainty. If so, how can humans (in Aim 2) judge how accurately AI’s learned reward function match their intent? For example, a suboptimal human performer might detect misalignment (maybe because AI is trying to act differently and better than them?) and impede AI that aims to learn to outperform them. For humans who are still learning what their preference might be, how can they interpret AI’s reward function without having discovered their own preferences?

- Aim 2.2 seems a little deviated from the rest of the proposed research.







3. Is the plan for carrying out the proposed activities well-reasoned, well- organized, and based on a sound rationale? Does the plan incorporate a mechanism to assess success?




The plan is well-reasoned and organized. The plan does incorporate evaluation.










4. How well qualified is the individual, team, or institution to conduct the proposed activities?




The PI has demonstrated a great track record of conducting similar research and also has done preliminary work to support each aim.







5. Are there adequate resources available to the PI (either at the home institution or through collaborations) to carry out the proposed activities?




Seems adequate.

draft a letter of recommendation for Chang Liu. Use he/him/his as his pronouns. based on the following self-intro.




My name is Chang Liu. I graduated as a master graduate of Computer Science from Tsinghua University in 2024. Before that, I received my bachelor degree of Agriculture from Zhejiang University in 2016, and worked for five years in visual effect, video editing and 3d modeling.

I began my HCI research in Tsinghua. My first independent project is called CalibRead, where I leverage users’ natural reading behavior to achieve implicit calibration of eye trackers. This paper has been accepted by IMWUT 2024 with me as the first author. Following that, I did a follow-up project--COMETIC, where I propose a similar implicit calibration method for front-camera based eye tracking on smartphones. By introducing a cursor to smartphones, I leverage the behavior during interaction for calibration. This paper has been submitted to CHI 2025, and is now under revision.




In our collaboration about overreliance,

1. I redesigned task 3 in the experiment, clarifying the task for participants.

2. I collaborated with Xinjie on data analysis.

(1) I summarized the behavioral features from both linear and nonlinear regression into two categories, and provided possible explanations based on the positive and negative correlations between these feature values and overreliance.

(2) I helped to filter variables with strong correlation in order to avoid multicollinearity.

(3) I proposed to use nonlinear regression to filter more convincing behavioral features after we discovered the linear fit ordinary linear square regression was terrible.

3. I proposed the experiment with interviews to collect potential findings as supplements for our quantitative analysis.

4. I develop a plugin for the experiment platform, ensuring the users could correctly access and copy the text in the page.

5. I and Qinyi worked together on preparing content for the experiment, deciding experiment procedure, recruiting participants and conducting the experiments.

6. About paper writing.

(1) I wrote Section 3 (Method) and the quantitative analysis in Section 4 (Findings).

(2) I made adjustments to Section 1 (Introduction) and Section 2 (Related Works).

(3) About a week before the submission deadline, I assigned the remaining tasks for fulfilling the paper and collaborated with Qinyi and Xinjie to ensure the paper was completed and submitted before the deadline.

 

Highlights

I am highly perseverent and always work consistently until the task is completed. I would also share my positive and motivating belief to my collaborators, offering support and encouragement throughout the research process. (Days before ddl, Qinyi and Xinjie were uncertain about submitting the paper on time. I convinced them that submitting the paper, even if not perfect, would allow us to receive valuable feedback from reviewers. With that in mind, we managed to submit the paper on time.)

I have a good understanding about how to complete an HCI paper, after completing two independent projects. Specifically, I am able to clarify the research question, plan the research process, evaluate the result, and write a paper that can clearly state my contributions.

I have strong project management skills. I am able to effectively define the final objectives and provide clear task assignments based on the current project progress, team capabilities, and the timeline. (I have demonstrated this ability both in the overreliance project and in the COMETIC project.)

I learn quickly and can rapidly adopt new and appropriate methods in response to new demands and changes. (In the overreliance project, when we implemented a nonlinear regression model, I learned the relevant concepts from scratch and effectively summarized the conclusions based on the regression results.)

I am passionate about helping others by sharing my skills and knowledge. I enjoy collaborating with others and actively contribute to problem-solving, therefore enhancing our collective expertise. (In the overreliance project, I helped Qinyi with program debugging, sharing practical techniques I use regularly.)

1) a paragraph that briefly introduces yourself (mainly academically)




    Xinjie is an ambitious undergraduate student at the South China University of Technology, where they have been deeply involved in data mining, networks, and LLM agents for the past two years. Xinjie's research primarily focuses on modifying connections and modeling relations, with their innovative approach to mining negative relations in networks using sign graph neural networks (one paper submission to the TKDE). Xinjie also proposed to integrate multi-view connections using graph theory and manifold (two papers accepted by WWW conference and TNNLS). In the realm of LLM agents, Xinjie has designed a novel LLM agent framework for generating stock reports with explainable news analysis (one paper accepted by WWW). He has also led to propose a new scenario for R&D for LLM agents, collaborating on a cutting-edge evolving strategy with Microsoft Research Asia, leading an open-source project with over 1,000 stars. Xinjie believes that optimization on interaction leads superior performance in various tasks on networks. He is determined to use own expertise of interaction level modification on networks and HCI perspective to investigate and answer sociological questions on upcoming social networks with comparable amount of AI and human coexist. 

    

    TKDE: IEEE Transactions on Knowledge and Data Engineering 

    TNNLS: IEEE Transactions on Neural Networks and Learning Systems

    WWW: ACM Web Conference

    







2) a list of highlights you want me to mention in the letter

   

    During the collaborated research in LLM overreliance project, here are some highlights of I hope can be selected mentioned in the letter:

    

    + Xinjie designed summary tasks for overreliance detection. This involved setting the objectives for the summary tasks, creating a 12-point injected prompt, and developing evaluation methods and metrics. Xinjie continuously improved the injected prompt for consistency and utilized a "think aloud" method with CoPilot to further refine the prompt.

    

    + Xinjie conducted an analysis of hallucination types and justified the design of the injected prompt. Meanwhile, Xinjie also uses statics tests (t-test, shapiro test) to justify the distribution type and consistent distribution between different groups, which is crucial for the experiment to be robust and reliable.

    

    + Xinjie established an experimental environment using Google Forms, WJX, and an online chat web platform. This allowed users to perform the tasks without the inconvenience of shared accounts, making the experiment more seamless and reliable.

    

    + Xinjie implemented additional features for user behavior collection using a Javascript listener and contributed to its development as a browser extension.

    

    + Xinjie processed and cleaned the raw data collected, converting it into statistical user behavior data suitable for analysis.

    

    + Xinjie developed analysis methods using both linear regression models (Ordinary Least Squares, OLS) and tree-based models (Gradient Boosting Decision Tree, GBDT). These were used to find correlations between user behavior and the overreliance score (metric). For the linear regression model, Xinjie used p-values to select significant features, while for the tree-based model, Xinjie employed SHAP values to interpret the model's output and feature correlations.

    

    + Xinjie conducted further analysis on the interaction between features and the overreliance score, identifying more detailed action patterns that may lead to overreliance.

    

    + Xinjie created visual representations of the data and results,and contributed to the writing of the research paper. This included sections on data collection, experiment setup, method descriptions, and findings.
